column330: Actually punish blatant violations. For example, I had a professor who posted no notes or solutions online, yet ALL of the international students walked into class each day with the notes and all had access to the previous semester solutions. column277: The notification of when we will receive housing and if we will receive housing is entirely unpredictable. Then we are only given a few days to accept/reject the offer. There are no photos of the units posted or floor plans provided. I was out of the country when I was notified of my apartment placing and very frustrated that I was not given time to see or consider the unit. The transfer process is also not straightforward. There is no clear process to follow or indication that we are guaranteed to get a unit that we prefer to the current unit we are placed in.

column345: The housing payment is due in full the first month of graduate student life (approximately $6000, including the $1000 due over the summer to secure a spot). This is somewhat unfair and unreasonable to students who do not receive financial support from their parents and are not warned about this prior to requesting/accepting housing. It is somewhat unfair to be expected to pay $6000 before receiving an initial paycheck from Columbia University as a new graduate student.

column253: There needs to be SEAS graduate-specific mental health counseling. When I tried getting an appointment with Columbia Mental Health Services in the middle of the Fall 2018 semester, they were read to refer me to an outside therapist. That was not convenient for me.     The reasoning was they did not consider me at-risk, so could not find someone I'd be able to see until the end of that semester. That was very discouraging for me, and it felt that, just like everything else at Columbia, even counseling is a competition and a numbers game.    I was very disappointed in Columbia Counseling Services for this reason.

column68: The finance information on SSOL is truly terrible, and doesn't reflect what's going on in my account -- e.g. sometimes charges and credits are *combined* in SSOL, which makes it nearly impossible figure out what is going on.     Additionally, having to pay my rent on SSOL is a nightmare. I may have $10k+ outstanding charges in tuition, which will eventually be reimbursed (as I am a PhD) yet this is not separated from the much smaller amount I pay in rent. It is not stated anywhere on SSOL when my rent is *due*, and it's unclear how it's related to other school charges (which may be due at different times).     For example, I got a late fee applied to my account. It took many emails with several different people to figure out where this late fee came from!

column253: I have been in pain every day for months because I've had to defer dental work. Dental insurance is 10% discount at Columbia's faculty practice. The endodontist I saw under Columbia's insurance promised me that she could "try her best" to do a root canal on me. A normal endodontist has one job: do root canals! Columbia's faculty practice is a sorry excuse because it has young, inexperienced dentists who are dentists only part time.I will also simply refuse to get mental health care at Columbia because  it requires a referral from CPS. It's not entirely unusual for universities to force out students after becoming aware of mental health issues, so it's just not worth the risk to go to CPS.

column277: If I am paying for my apartment, I should be able to get a chance to have a look at my place before accepting the housing offer. All I receive is a floor plan of my room. I had no other choice than accepting the offer since otherwise, I would have to reapply and wait uncertain amount of time for another housing assignment. When I moved into the place, I did not like my apartment yet I had no option other than staying. After a few weeks, I realized that the old furnitures at my apartment had bed bugs which create a huge problem for me in the middle of an already rough first semester. If only students who are offered an housing assignment were allowed to view their spaces before moving in, they would be able to make a better decision. UAH has to really step up their game in making this a smooth process. Like any off-campus housing (OCHA) offers provide you with pictures of the living space and furnitures as well as a time for the visit. The Columbia Residential application should include them when they give an assignment to the student.

column345: I think it would be great to have a lounge area specific to each department (i.e. BME lounge) so that students have a place to do homework together and socialize.  We use the BME conference room when it's available but it usually isn't during the day.  Additionally, my biggest source of frustration with this school is the lack of info provided at orientation and the administration's willingness to help.  Any resource I've uncovered I've had to figure out by myself (e.g. obtaining financial aid, gym memberships, finding places to eat on campus, finding places to study).  Additionally, out of the 8 classes I've taken, only 2 of my professors care about me as a person.  The rest are unwilling to help me understand the material, which is unacceptable given how much we pay to attend.

column277: I had ranked a dorm last year because it claimed that a cost for a dorm would be between $800-$1000.  So I ranked dorm before apartment for that reason.  However, when I got an assignment, I got a dorm that was $1250 a month.  If I knew I would be paying that much for a dorm, I would have just ranked apartment first since it's the same price.  The transfer process was difficult at first because after filling out the transfer application in November, they had told me that I might be able to move in April/May 2019.  I didn't want to wait that long, but I didn't have a choice. Thankfully, I got a notice that my dorm was going to undergo construction in May 2019, so everyone needed to move out.  Hence, my transfer application was bumped up, and I have officially transferred as of March 2019.  It would be nice to be given floor plans of the apartments during the transfer process or be able to see units as if one was apartment hunting prior to ranking units in the Selection Rounds.  Otherwise, Columbia Residential was very helpful during the transfer process.
